        <mxCell id="CzHw7VR60xhRQRThsIUk-41" parent="1" style="swimlane;html=1;fontStyle=0;childLayout=stackLayout;horizontal=1;startSize=30;fillColor=#e0e0e0;horizontalStack=0;resizeParent=1;resizeLast=0;collapsible=1;marginBottom=0;swimlaneFillColor=#ffffff;align=center;rounded=1;shadow=0;comic=0;labelBackgroundColor=none;strokeWidth=1;fontFamily=Verdana;fontSize=12" value="&lt;b&gt;compile_ionization (cstool.py)&lt;/b&gt;" vertex="1">
          <mxGeometry height="360" width="290" x="1590" y="1160" as="geometry" />
        </mxCell>
        <mxCell id="CzHw7VR60xhRQRThsIUk-42" parent="CzHw7VR60xhRQRThsIUk-41" style="text;html=1;strokeColor=none;fillColor=none;spacingLeft=4;spacingRight=4;whiteSpace=wrap;overflow=hidden;rotatable=0;points=[[0,0.5],[1,0.5]];portConstraint=eastwest;" value="&lt;div&gt;- Compute the tables required to sample ionization events. Also used to determine if excitation is valence or inner shell. The sampling table is constructed not with actual energy loss omega as a parameter, but with fractional energy loss. I.e. between 0 and 1, which if you then multiply by the electron energy will give the actual energy loss.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;" vertex="1">
          <mxGeometry height="110" width="290" y="30" as="geometry" />
        </mxCell>
        <mxCell id="CzHw7VR60xhRQRThsIUk-104" parent="CzHw7VR60xhRQRThsIUk-41" style="text;html=1;strokeColor=none;fillColor=none;spacingLeft=4;spacingRight=4;whiteSpace=wrap;overflow=hidden;rotatable=0;points=[[0,0.5],[1,0.5]];portConstraint=eastwest;" value="&lt;div&gt;- Write the electron energies, loss fractions for which the icdf is calculated and the icdf itself to the .mat material file.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;Formatting explanation:&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;Sampling the exported icdf table first requires selecting an omega vs probability table corresponding to a primary electron energy E. Next, a uniform distribution is drawn and an energy loss omega is chosen using that table. In the main Nebula code, the shell with the largest binding energy below this omega is chosen, because it is expected to dominate the result. This approximation is made for a significant speed advantage.&lt;/div&gt;" vertex="1">
          <mxGeometry height="220" width="290" y="140" as="geometry" />
        </mxCell>
        <mxCell id="CzHw7VR60xhRQRThsIUk-45" parent="1" style="swimlane;html=1;fontStyle=0;childLayout=stackLayout;horizontal=1;startSize=30;fillColor=#e0e0e0;horizontalStack=0;resizeParent=1;resizeLast=0;collapsible=1;marginBottom=0;swimlaneFillColor=#ffffff;align=center;rounded=1;shadow=0;comic=0;labelBackgroundColor=none;strokeWidth=1;fontFamily=Verdana;fontSize=12" value="&lt;b&gt;elf_full_penn (penn.py)&lt;/b&gt;" vertex="1">
          <mxGeometry height="180" width="290" x="1920" y="610" as="geometry" />
        </mxCell>
        <mxCell id="CzHw7VR60xhRQRThsIUk-46" parent="CzHw7VR60xhRQRThsIUk-45" style="text;html=1;strokeColor=none;fillColor=none;spacingLeft=4;spacingRight=4;whiteSpace=wrap;overflow=hidden;rotatable=0;points=[[0,0.5],[1,0.5]];portConstraint=eastwest;" value="&lt;div&gt;- The minimum possible energy loss is given by specified optical data. The maximum possible energy loss can be specified.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;" vertex="1">
          <mxGeometry height="50" width="290" y="30" as="geometry" />
        </mxCell>
